Thought this would enlighten the mood a little!!

  SENIORS GIVING BIRTH



 With all the new technology regarding fertility, recently a 65-year-old

 woman was able to give birth to a baby. When she was discharged from the

 hospital and went home, her relatives came to visit.



 May we see the new baby?&quot; one asked.



 &quot;Not yet,&quot; said the mother &quot;I&#39;ll make coffee and we can visit for a while

 first.&quot;



 Thirty minutes had passed, and another relative asked, &quot;May we see the new

 baby now?&quot;



 &quot;No, not yet,&quot; said the mother.



 After another few minutes had elapsed, they asked again, &quot;May we see the

 baby now?&quot;



  &quot;No, not yet,&quot; replied the mother.



  Growing very impatient, they asked, &quot;Well, when can we see the baby?&quot;



 &quot;WHEN HE CRIES!&quot; she told them.



 &quot;WHEN HE CRIES?&quot; they asked. &quot;Why do we have to wait until he cries?&quot;



 BECAUSE I FORGOT WHERE I PUT HIM .. OK?







From: EVP-ITC@yahoogroups.com [mailto:EVP-ITC@yahoogroups.com] On Behalf Of
Robin Searcy Henson
Sent: Thursday, January 03, 2008 4:51 PM
To: EVP-ITC@yahoogroups.com
Subject: Re: [EVP-ITC] Not to be a wet blanket



Hiya Bruce,



Besides the broken cellphone I was going to mention an old Medasonics
Doppler that got damaged from amniotic fluid during a birth I was attending
a few years ago.  I think both these gadgets could have potential in the
field of EVP-ITC research!



I actually did listen to all your files last night and was very impressed.
VERY impressed!  I don&#39;t comment very often because I feel extremely
intimidated by what you all are accomplishing here, and all I have is my
little digital recorder and no knowledge of electronics at all.  I really
think your work is awesome.  



I have a wandering mind but will do my best to stay on topic from now on.



Robin/OR







